<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO SARAH</font><br>
<tt>Sun Feb  9 16:15:39 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To Sarah,<br><br>
Thanks for your thoughtful reply to my question. As you can see from these posts, there are many trying to work their way through many difficulties of the Vietnam War legacy. I include myself in that group.<br><br>
Understanding protestors is very important in my personal journey toward resolving many of the conflicts, memories, regrets, and emotional pain about my Vietnam experience.<br><br>
From your comments, I sense a conviction that the protest movement in &quot;form&quot; is dimensionless in terms of individuals who may be on either side. There is a cause. Destruction of the object of the cause is unthinkable and counterproductive. From your view, abuse of Vietnam Veterans ran contrary to the cause of bringing the people home and ending the conflict. I feel you are an honest person in your comments, and that alone helps in ways perhaps you do not understand.<br><br>
If we can take this another step forward, another question arises. Who were these people abusing returning Vietnam Veterans and what were their motives? I fail to see any logic in abusing returning Vietnam Veterans in order to stop a war that the Veterans had just lived through and survived to return.<br><br>
Were these people just some extremist fringe of psychologically disturbed people, or were there other forces at work about which I am unaware?<br><br>
I would appreciate your continued thoughts.<br><br>
Thanks!<br><br>
Arthur Varanelli
